54":"1254","1287":"1287","about 1300":"about 1300","about 1286":"about 1286","4 April 1264":"4 April 1264","1307":"1307","Warminster, Wiltshire, England":"Warminster, Wiltshire, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Warminister,,Wiltshire,England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mauduit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Mawditt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mawditt","meanings":["Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>mal-duit</i> ‘badly brought up, ill educated’ (Latin  <i>male doctus</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Warren","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is of Norman origin, a coalescence of two different surnames, one derived from a Germanic personal name based on the element <i>war(in)</i> ‘guard’ and the other from a place in Normandy called <i>La Varenne</i> ‘the game park’. The Norman personal name survived at least into the 17th century in Yorkshire, where it was particularly associated with the Scargill family. In America this name has sometimes been chosen in honour of  General Joseph Warren , the first hero of the American Revolution, who was killed at  Bunker Hill  (  1775 ). Among modern influences on the choice of the name has been the film actor  Warren Beatty  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Warren Mauduit was born in 1254, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Mauduit, was 26 and his mother, Eugenia FitzWarin, was 27. He married Elizabeth de Lisle about 1286, in Warminster, Wiltshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 26 September 1300, in his hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1254–26 Sep 1300":"1254–26. september 1300","1248–1271":"1248–1271","1254–1300":"1254–1300","1260–1300":"